<HEADLINE>
<P>
DUCKS TIED UP IN STRETCH; HOCKEY: ANAHEIM SQUANDERS THREE-GOAL LEAD. TORONTO 
SCORES WITH 2:24 LEFT IN THIRD PERIOD FOR 3-3 DEADLOCK. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ELLIOTT TEAFORD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Happiness came in measured doses for the Mighty Ducks Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
 They tied the Toronto Maple Leafs, 3-3, in front of 15,728 at Maple Leaf 
Gardens. And that should have ranked as one of the season's best, most pleasing 
performances. 
</P>
<P>
 But the Ducks had a three-goal lead late in the second period and let it slip 
away. 
</P>
<P>
 They led, 3-2, with less than three minutes to play when Toronto defenseman 
Dmitri Mironov scored the game-tying goal on a shot from the blue line. 
</P>
<P>
 Goaltender Guy Hebert kept the Maple Leafs scoreless for more than 36 minutes, 
but never saw Mironov's shot. Hebert, who defeated Toronto, 1-0, on Dec. 15, 
said the Ducks should have won again. 
</P>
<P>
 So did Coach Ron Wilson, defenseman Randy Ladouceur and left wing Troy Loney. 
</P>
<P>
 Only when the Ducks considered the notion of an expansion team winning and 
tying against the Maple Leafs in their two Toronto appearances this season, did 
their spirits lift. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's quite an accomplishment to come in here and take three out of four 
points," Wilson said after the Ducks improved to 12-12-1 away from Anaheim 
Arena. They are 3-0-1 in their last four on the road. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ducks also extended their unbeaten streak in Canada to seven and stopped 
Toronto's six-game winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm disappointed we didn't come out of here with another point," Wilson said. 
"But one point will do." 
</P>
<P>
 Ladouceur, playing for the first time in four games after bruising his thigh 
against Detroit Jan. 10, put it this way: 
</P>
<P>
 "The big picture looks pretty good. Three points in Maple Leaf Gardens is 
pretty good hockey." 
</P>
<P>
 Loney scored two second-period goals putting the Ducks ahead, 3-0, at the 
12:54 mark. 
</P>
<P>
 Toronto seemed punchless for long stretches -- going without a shot on goal 
for more than 10 minutes to start the second period, for instance. 
</P>
<P>
 But when the Maple Leafs finally came to life, they were swift and decisive 
around the Duck net. 
</P>
<P>
 Dave Ellett scored on a shot from the blue line at the 16:33 mark of the 
second period, then Dave Andreychuk scored on a backhander from the slot a 
little more than two minutes later. Doug Gilmour's assist on Andreychuk's goal 
was the 600th of his career. 
</P>
<P>
 In the third period, Hebert kept the swarming Maple Leafs scoreless until 2:24 
remained in the game, when Mironov scored. 
</P>
<P>
 "I lost sight of it (the puck)," Hebert said later. "I thought about going 
down, but I wanted to stay on my feet in case they dumped it into the corner. 
They'd been doing that all night." 
</P>
<P>
 Instead, Mironov fired away with several players blocking Hebert's view, and 
the puck went between his pads and into the net. Mike Eastwood won a faceoff in 
the right circle, sending the puck back to Mironov. 
</P>
<P>
 Mironov was about as unlikely a hero for Toronto as you could get, what with 
Gilmour and Andreychuk the NHL's third- and fourth-leading scorers buzzing 
Hebert in the third period. 
</P>
<P>
 Gilmour has 15 goals and 52 assists and Andreychuk has 38 goals and 28 
assists. Mironov scored only his fifth goal, his first since Jan 8. 
</P>
<P>
 Hebert stopped 29 shots, but wasn't content with a tie, especially when the 
Ducks controlled the 
</P>
<P>
 game for so long. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think we played an excellent game," he said. "We frustrated them all night 
long and I think we got under their skin. We probably should have sneaked out 
of here with another win." 
</P>
<P>
 There was no argument from any of his teammates, but they seemed pleased 
enough with the consolation prize. 
</P>
<P>
 "We'll take the tie in this building," Loney said. 
</P>
<P>
 Duck Notes 
</P>
<P>
 Right wing Steven King, who played in a 4-3 loss to Vancouver on Sunday, did 
not play Tuesday. King continues to be bothered by a sprained left shoulder and 
his status is day-to-day. . . . The Ducks announced that $322,566.85 was raised 
for fire relief from the Dec. 9 exhibition against the Kings. All proceeds will 
be donated to chapters of the American Red Cross in Los Angeles and Orange 
counties. 
</P>
<P>
 * KINGS SEE STARS: Dallas gets a three-goal lead early and beats the Kings, 
5-3, in a bruising game. C4 
</P>
</TEXT>
