<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: IRVINE; NEIGHBORHOOD PARK PLANS MAKE PROGRESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Plans to transform a narrow 1.3-mile railroad right-of-way into a neighborhood 
recreation area took a step forward this month with a meeting between Northwood 
residents and a noted urban designer. 
</P>
<P>
 Residents packed a local middle school one Saturday morning two weeks ago to 
discuss the fledgling park's design and give their input to San Francisco 
architect Lawrence Halprin, who volunteered his time to work on the project. 
</P>
<P>
 The unusual daylong dialogue produced general agreement on many ideas for the 
65-foot-wide sliver of land that runs roughly between Culver Drive and Jeffrey 
Road. 
</P>
<P>
 Residents said they want an eight-foot-wide walking path to run through the 
middle of the park. 
</P>
<P>
 Many participants also agreed that the park should include benches and trash 
cans but no public restrooms. It should also be connected to nearby Silkwood 
Park and to Westwood Basics Plus Elementary School, the group suggested. 
</P>
<P>
 Other ideas included: 
</P>
<P>
 * Planting trees and shrubbery around the area. 
</P>
<P>
 * Using drought-resistant plants when possible. 
</P>
<P>
 * Installing timer-activated lights throughout the park. 
</P>
<P>
 * Taking safety measures to protect pedestrians who must cross busy streets 
while using the trail. 
</P>
<P>
 A design consultant will now draw more detailed plans for the park and present 
them to the city in March. The project is expected to cost several million 
dollars. 
</P>
<P>
 The issue of how to use the right-of-way has been a contentious one ever since 
the railroad tracks were removed about a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
 Many residents fought a proposal to use the land as part of a regional bike 
path. 
</P>
<P>
 And while those who attended the meeting did not agree on all points, city 
officials said the event represented progress. 
</P>
<P>
 "Really, I went in skeptical," said Councilwoman Paula Werner, who attended 
the meeting. "This process has been going on for years and there's been 
divisiveness. But during the course of the day, I think we were really able to 
think and plan the kind of park we want. I was pleased with the entire 
course."SHELBY GRAD 
</P>
</TEXT>
