<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: SAN CLEMENTE; CITY TO CONSIDER BID TO DEMOLISH 5 HOMES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 More than 10 years after being condemned, demolition of five homes in Verde 
Canyon will start next week if the City Council tonight approves a contractor's 
bid for the work. 
</P>
<P>
 The homes are among the 10 destroyed or condemned after a massive landslide in 
Verde Canyon in December, 1983. 
</P>
<P>
 The council will consider a low bid of $34,000, submitted by Fynok American 
Co. of Inglewood, to raze the five structures. The cost of demolition will be 
charged to the owners as a lien against the property. 
</P>
<P>
 "The houses were declared a nuisance because of the unstable soil conditions 
beneath them," said city building official Trang Huynh. "We want to make sure 
this site is cleaned up. These houses can't continue to just sit there." 
</P>
<P>
 The condemned and boarded-up structures have occasionally been used by 
transients over the years. 
</P>
<P>
 Lawsuits over the disaster held up demolition for several years. City 
officials were ready to proceed with the work last year, but a housing 
development proposal for the canyon area halted the city's plans. 
</P>
<P>
 However, when it became apparent that the proposal to build 30 homes at the 
bottom of Verde Canyon was moving slowly, the city pushed forward with the 
demolition plan. FRANK MESSINA 
</P>
</TEXT>
